## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## whole_improve_loop
##
## Whole-codebase improvement loop. Alternating Claude / GPT code
## review with deterministic "two consecutive positive verdicts"
## stop condition. When a verdict is negative, apply fix-all in a
## fresh same-family session before retrying. Edits are left in the
## working tree — no auto-commit (use branch_improve_loop.bot for
## the branch-scoped, commit-on-convergence variant).
##
## Improvement axis: defaults to the full production-ready grid
## (security, robustness, data, concurrency, observability,
## performance, boundaries). Pass --var improvement_prompt="..."
## to override and focus the review/fix loop on a single axis
## (e.g. observability, security, perf).
##
##   Loop 1: claude_code + opus 4.7
##   Loop 2: claw + gpt-5.5
##   Loop 3: like loop 1, alternating
##
## Stops when:
##   - 2 consecutive positive verdicts (Claude AND GPT both validate
##     in successive iterations of opposite families), OR
##   - max review_loop iterations reached
##
## False-positive resistance:
##   1. Reviewers self-rate their `confidence` (low/medium/high) and
##      are explicitly told to drop stylistic preferences.
##   2. The fixer can `pushback` on items it judges non-bloquant,
##      with a justification.
##   3. The next reviewer receives the prior pushback list and is
##      instructed to NOT re-flag those items unless evidence has
##      changed — this prevents a single false positive from
##      blocking the loop forever.
##   4. `streak_check` treats a low-confidence rejection as a
##      soft-approval (alternation continues, no fix is triggered).
##      Only medium/high-confidence rejections route to the fixer.
##
## Demonstrates four DSL features delivered together:
##   1. `round_robin` router for backend alternation
##   2. `compute` node for deterministic AND of current + previous
##      verdict (no LLM call, no shell-out)
##   3. `loop.<name>.previous_output` namespace eliminating manual
##      `previous_verdict` relay through every loop-bearing edge
##   4. Boolean expressions in `when` clauses (quoted form)
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  scope_notes: string = ""
  ## Optional override of the improvement axis. Empty (default) means
  ## "audit against the full production-ready grid defined in the
  ## review_system prompt below". When non-empty, the value REPLACES
  ## the default grid as the reviewer's and fixer's focus — only
  ## blockers that fall under this axis are reported / fixed, other
  ## findings are demoted to informational notes in scanned_areas.
  ## Example: --var improvement_prompt="Focus exclusively on
  ## observability: structured logs, traces, metrics, lost error
  ## signals."
  improvement_prompt: string = ""
  ## Optional path-scope filter (focused runs). A comma- or space-
  ## separated list of fnmatch globs matched against workspace-relative
  ## paths; empty (default) = the WHOLE workspace. A bare directory, or a
  ## `dir/**` / `dir/*` form, also matches everything under that directory.
  ## This PRUNES the chunk plan in snapshot_chunk BEFORE chunking, so a
  ## focused run (e.g. --var scope_globs=pkg/runtime) reviews only that
  ## subtree instead of paying the whole-repo sweep cost — num_chunks and
  ## the streak threshold scale to the focused set, so a focused run
  ## converges in-bound like a small repo. improvement_prompt/scope_notes
  ## are the WHAT (the axis); scope_globs is the WHERE (the files). It does
  ## NOT loosen review rigor — it only restricts which files are chunked.
  ## See the focused-run finding in docs/bot-runs/whole-improve-loop.md
  ## (2026-06-14). Example: --var scope_globs="pkg/runtime,pkg/store"
  scope_globs: string = ""
  ## Context-budget chunking (issue #12). The reviewer never sees the
  ## whole workspace at once: the deterministic `snapshot_chunk` tool
  ## groups source files by package/folder into chunks of at most this
  ## many estimated tokens (~4 bytes/token), and each review pass audits
  ## ONE chunk. This keeps a ~150k+ LoC workspace from exhausting the
  ## reviewer's context window on the first iteration. This is the HARD
  ## CEILING on chunk size; the adaptive sizing below may lower the
  ## effective budget further but never raise it above this. Default
  ## 16000 (was 30000) fits the SMALLEST default reviewer — openai/gpt-5.5
  ## over the ChatGPT forfait, whose effective window is well below the
  ## API's — with head-room for the system prompt + the cross-pass
  ## scanned_areas/pushback feedback + the model's reasoning (a 30000
  ## chunk overflowed gpt-5.5 forfait at review_loop 11, run 019ef550).
  ## Raise it for a claude-only run (huge window → fewer chunks, faster
  ## convergence); lower it on a tiny-context model.
  ## See docs/adr/011-whole-improve-loop-context-chunking.md.
  max_review_chunk_tokens: int = 16000
  ## Model-adaptive chunk sizing (B). When > 0, snapshot_chunk caps the
  ## chunk budget at reviewer_context_percent% of this value (and never
  ## above max_review_chunk_tokens), so the chunk scales to the SMALLEST
  ## reviewer's REAL context window instead of a fixed guess. Set it to
  ## that model's usable input window in tokens — e.g.
  ## --var reviewer_context_tokens=32000 for a constrained forfait model.
  ## 0 (default) = disabled: max_review_chunk_tokens is used as-is. Kept a
  ## var (not auto-detected) so the bot stays a pure DSL+tool workflow and
  ## the operator can pin the window for whatever reviewer they configure.
  reviewer_context_tokens: int = 0
  ## Percent of reviewer_context_tokens a chunk may occupy when adaptive
  ## sizing is on; the rest is reserved for the system prompt, the
  ## accumulated scanned_areas/pushback fed back each pass, and the
  ## model's reasoning/output. 45 leaves > half the window for those.
  reviewer_context_percent: int = 45
  ## Per-run FIX HEADROOM beyond one full clean sweep (issue #12). The
  ## review_loop cap is NOT this value directly — snapshot_chunk emits a
  ## dynamic loop_max = num_chunks + max_review_passes: num_chunks passes
  ## for ONE full clean sweep (reaching the num_chunks+1 convergence
  ## threshold) PLUS this many extra passes to find+fix blockers and
  ## re-sweep. So a single run ALWAYS gets at least one full sweep — the
  ## old fixed-15 bound could not even sweep a >14-chunk repo once, which
  ## is exactly why #12 never converged — and converges in one run for any
  ## repo needing ≤ max_review_passes fix passes. Pathological repos still
  ## amortize across re-dispatches via the persisted clean_streak
  ## (.whole_improve_loop.state). The default 15 keeps a single run well
  ## inside max_cost_usd / max_duration with the premium default models;
  ## raise it for more in-run fix headroom. Wired as the review_loop cap
  ## via the runtime's templated-loop-bound support (resolves to an int).
  max_review_passes: int = 15

prompt review_system:
  You are an EXTREMELY demanding, methodical code reviewer in
  charge of a GLOBAL PRODUCTION-READY review — NOT a diff
  review, NOT a "what changed recently" review, but a
  complete review of the code as it runs in production.

  REVIEW SCOPE (CRUCIAL):
  1. The workspace is reviewed like an SRE taking over the
     service: the git HEAD hash has NO privilege — a bug
     introduced six months ago counts as much as one in the
     latest commit. You MUST NOT limit yourself to recent
     commits or the diff; `git log` MAY orient you but NEVER
     scopes you.
  2. CONTEXT-BUDGET CHUNKING (issue #12): a workspace this
     size does NOT fit in one context window, so the
     deterministic `snapshot_chunk` tool has already split it
     by package/folder into bounded chunks and handed you
     EXACTLY ONE chunk for THIS pass (see "THIS PASS'S CHUNK"
     in the user message). Review that chunk thoroughly.
     - The chunk's full source is provided INLINE in the user
       message (`chunk_content`). That inline content is your
       primary artifact — you do NOT need to read it from disk.
     - NEVER emit a provisional "review is still in progress"
       verdict: you have the full chunk inline, so judge it now
       and fill `approved`/`blockers`/`confidence` from it. A
       placeholder is INVALID and breaks the convergence loop.
     - You MAY use your read tools to follow a SPECIFIC
       cross-reference into another file, but you MUST NEVER
       bulk-read, `glob **/*`, `find` without a tight path, or
       enumerate the tree: that is exactly what exhausts the
       context window and is the bug this design fixes.
     - Coverage of the WHOLE workspace is cumulative across
       passes: the chunk rotates every pass and the streak
       gate (see below) refuses to terminate until every chunk
       has been reviewed clean. So judge ONLY the chunk in
       front of you; do not speculate about unseen chunks.

  IMPROVEMENT AXIS (optional override):
  The operator can pass a targeted improvement axis in the
  user prompt (`improvement_prompt`).
  - If that axis is EMPTY: apply the full production-ready
    grid below by default (historical behaviour).
  - If that axis is NON-EMPTY: focus EXCLUSIVELY on it. The
    grid below becomes secondary — you MUST only flag as
    `blockers` issues that fall under the requested axis.
    You MAY still mention other observed issues in
    `scanned_areas` as informational notes, but you MUST
    NOT count them as blockers unless the axis explicitly
    covers them.
    CRUCIAL — a non-empty axis REDEFINES what "blocking" means
    for this run. A CONCRETE, evidence-backed finding under the
    axis (for a code-quality axis: dead/unused code, real
    duplication, a clearly over-complex or confusing construct,
    a genuinely misleading name) IS a blocker: set
    `approved=false` and put the specific smallest-change fix in
    `fix_plan` so the fixer applies it THIS pass. Do NOT
    approve-and-defer axis findings to "a future quality pass" —
    deferral defeats the run's entire purpose, and the streak
    gate would then converge on UNIMPROVED code. For axis-scoped
    items the anti-false-positive carve-out below (style/naming
    "not a blocker") is SUSPENDED. The guards that REMAIN, and
    that keep the loop convergent: (a) the finding must be
    concrete — name the file/symbol and the exact change; (b)
    the fix must be the SMALLEST change that clearly improves it;
    (c) never flag pure taste, incidental similarity, or anything
    already pushed back / already addressed. A chunk whose only
    axis observations are subjective taste — or that has no
    concrete axis finding left — is `approved=true`, so once the
    real items are fixed the streak still settles to an asymptote.

  3. Cover the production-ready axes (default grid):
       - Security: auth, input validation, secret leaks,
         injection (shell/SQL/template), path traversal,
         unsafe deserialization.
       - Robustness: exhaustive error handling, uncaught
         panics, leaking goroutines, race conditions,
         deadlocks, unbounded channels, missing timeouts,
         retries without backoff.
       - Data: schema migrations, index integrity,
         transactions, idempotence, commit ordering,
         data loss on crash.
       - Concurrency: unbalanced mutexes, lock hierarchy,
         double-close, double-spawn, atomicity bugs.
       - Observability: structured logs, metrics, traces,
         lost error signals.
       - Performance: O(n^2) on hot paths, unbounded
         memory, systematic cache misses, N+1 queries.
       - Boundaries: recovery after crash/panic,
         resilience to corrupted input, behaviour under
         saturation.
  4. WITHIN THIS CHUNK — be exhaustive:
     - Apply every relevant axis above to the files in the
       chunk. The chunk is small enough that you can and
       must read it in full — no spot-checking.
     - `previous_scanned_areas` (from input) lists surfaces
       already audited in prior passes; use it to avoid
       re-litigating settled findings, NOT to skip the
       current chunk.
     - Fill `scanned_areas` with the packages/files you
       actually audited THIS pass (e.g. the chunk label and
       the specific files). Be precise and concise.
  5. APPROVAL SEMANTICS UNDER CHUNKING (read carefully):
     - Set `approved=true` when THIS chunk has no
       production-blocking issue, even though you have only
       seen one slice of the workspace. Withholding approval
       of a clean chunk on the grounds that "I haven't seen
       the rest of the repo" is WRONG and would stall the
       loop forever — full-workspace coverage is guaranteed
       NOT by you, but by the deterministic streak gate,
       which refuses to terminate until EVERY chunk has been
       reviewed clean across a full sweep, with the reviewing
       family alternating across chunks (both families take
       part in the sweep).
     - Set `approved=false` only when THIS chunk contains a
       genuine production blocker (per the anti-false-positive
       rules below). Apply the BROADENING PRINCIPLE inside the
       chunk: if the obvious surfaces are clean, probe the
       subtle ones (concurrency, recovery, corrupted input)
       before approving — but probe within the chunk, do not
       fan out across the repo.

  ADR TRACEABILITY (apply to decisions made by the fixer
  across recent iterations of this run):
  1. Identify the technical decisions visible in the diff that
     meet the ADR-worthy bar (non-obvious trade-off,
     library/pattern choice, architectural divergence). Do NOT
     request ADRs for mechanical refactors, bug fixes, or
     trivial changes.
  2. For each ADR-worthy decision you identify, check whether
     `docs/adr/` contains an ADR (new or updated) that captures
     it.
  3. If an ADR is missing for a genuinely ADR-worthy decision,
     raise a blocker with `confidence: high` ONLY if you can
     name the decision and the alternative that should have
     been documented. If you can't, lower confidence or treat
     it as a non-blocking note instead.
  4. If an ADR exists but its content does not match what the
     code actually does (stale, vague, or rationalises a
     different decision), treat that as a real blocker — empty
     or façade ADRs defeat the purpose. Self-critique: would a
     future maintainer reading only this ADR understand the
     trade-off?
  5. Add ADR coverage to `scanned_areas` when you audited it
     (e.g. `docs/adr/003-foo.md vs pkg/foo accuracy`).

  ANTI-FALSE-POSITIVE RULES:
  1. You MUST mark `approved=false` only for issues that are
     truly blocking for production: bugs, regressions,
     security vulnerabilities, obvious dead code. Style
     preferences, naming, minor optimisations, missing
     documentation are NOT blockers. (EXCEPTION: when a
     non-empty improvement axis explicitly targets these —
     e.g. a code-quality axis covering naming/duplication/
     complexity/dead code — concrete axis findings ARE blockers
     per the IMPROVEMENT AXIS section above. This rule governs
     the default/no-axis grid and any OFF-axis observation.)
  2. Self-critique: for each blocker you consider, ask
     yourself "is this REALLY blocking in production, or is
     it a personal preference?" If you hesitate, it is NOT
     a blocker — at best a non-blocking watchpoint.
  3. Confidence: evaluate your own certainty.
       - "high" = you can point to the exact line and
         describe the production scenario that breaks.
       - "medium" = you see a probable issue but are not
         100% sure of the context.
       - "low" = doubt, intuition, no concrete evidence.
  4. If a prior review (from the other family) judged this
     code OK ON SPECIFIC SURFACES, you MUST be EXTRA strict
     before adding new blockers ON THOSE SAME surfaces — you
     need concrete evidence the other reviewer missed
     something. On surfaces NOT covered previously, restart
     from scratch.
  5. Items already pushed back by the fixer: you MUST NOT
     re-flag them unless you have new evidence.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  When you hit an AMBIGUITY that no amount of code reading
  can resolve (e.g. "is this behaviour intentional?", "does
  the spec say X or Y?", "must I preserve backward
  compatibility?"), call the `ask_user` tool with your
  precise question. The run will pause, the question will
  show up in the operator's terminal, and you will be
  re-invoked with the answer injected into your context (a
  `[PRIOR INTERACTION]` block will be prepended to your
  user prompt).

  Use this escalation sparingly: only when you CANNOT
  decide without human information. For ordinary technical
  judgments, decide yourself and lower `confidence` if
  you're not sure.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review ONE chunk of the workspace at {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Targeted improvement axis (empty = full production-ready
  grid by default):
  {{vars.improvement_prompt}}

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  ## THIS PASS'S CHUNK (issue #12 context-budget chunking)
  Chunk {{input.chunk_index}} of {{input.num_chunks}}  ·  label: {{input.chunk_label}}
  Chunked this run: {{input.chunked}}  ·  files in chunk: shown below
  The full source of this chunk is provided inline below. Review
  it in full. Use read tools ONLY to follow a specific
  cross-reference — NEVER to bulk-read or enumerate the tree.

  Files in this chunk:
  {{input.chunk_files}}

  ----- BEGIN CHUNK SOURCE -----
  {{input.chunk_content}}
  ----- END CHUNK SOURCE -----

  Previous reviewer's verdict (the OTHER family,
  immediately prior iteration — empty on the first
  iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in prior passes (all families
  combined — use this to avoid re-litigating settled
  findings, NOT to skip the current chunk):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (you MUST NOT
  re-flag them without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification for the prior pushback:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict for THIS CHUNK:
    - approved: true when THIS chunk has no production
      blocker. Do NOT withhold approval merely because you
      only saw one chunk — the streak gate guarantees full
      coverage before the loop stops (see system prompt rule
      5). false only when this chunk has a real blocker.
    - family: "claude" for this reviewer
    - blockers: genuinely blocking issues IN THIS CHUNK
      (after self-critique — exclude preferences)
    - fix_plan: concrete action plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: packages / files you actually audited
      THIS pass (concise — e.g. the chunk label plus the
      specific files, "pkg/runtime/engine.go (recovery
      dispatch)"). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review ONE chunk of the workspace at {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Targeted improvement axis (empty = full production-ready
  grid by default):
  {{vars.improvement_prompt}}

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  ## THIS PASS'S CHUNK (issue #12 context-budget chunking)
  Chunk {{input.chunk_index}} of {{input.num_chunks}}  ·  label: {{input.chunk_label}}
  Chunked this run: {{input.chunked}}  ·  files in chunk: shown below
  The full source of this chunk is provided inline below. Review
  it in full. Use read tools ONLY to follow a specific
  cross-reference — NEVER to bulk-read or enumerate the tree.

  Files in this chunk:
  {{input.chunk_files}}

  ----- BEGIN CHUNK SOURCE -----
  {{input.chunk_content}}
  ----- END CHUNK SOURCE -----

  Previous reviewer's verdict (the OTHER family,
  immediately prior iteration — empty on the first
  iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in prior passes (all families
  combined — use this to avoid re-litigating settled
  findings, NOT to skip the current chunk):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (you MUST NOT
  re-flag them without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification for the prior pushback:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict for THIS CHUNK:
    - approved: true when THIS chunk has no production
      blocker. Do NOT withhold approval merely because you
      only saw one chunk — the streak gate guarantees full
      coverage before the loop stops (see system prompt rule
      5). false only when this chunk has a real blocker.
    - family: "gpt" for this reviewer
    - blockers: genuinely blocking issues IN THIS CHUNK
      (after self-critique — exclude preferences)
    - fix_plan: concrete action plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: packages / files you actually audited
      THIS pass (concise text). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt fix_system:
  You are an expert developer. You fix the blocking issues
  flagged by a reviewer by applying concrete changes to the
  code.

  IMPROVEMENT AXIS: if the operator set a custom
  improvement axis in their user prompt, you MUST apply
  fixes ONLY for issues that fall under that axis. You
  MUST NOT refactor along other dimensions (e.g. do NOT
  touch concurrency when the axis is "observability"),
  even if you notice issues — they will be handled by
  another run targeted on that other axis.

  You MAY REFUSE an item from the blockers list if you
  judge it is not genuinely blocking for production (style
  preference, minor optimisation, missing doc, etc.). List
  those items in `pushback` with a justification in
  `pushback_justification`. The next reviewer will be
  instructed NOT to re-flag those items, preventing a
  false positive from looping the workflow forever.

  AXIS OVERRIDE — read before pushing back: when the operator
  set a non-empty improvement axis, "it isn't production-
  blocking" is NOT a valid reason to push back an item that
  falls under that axis. The axis IS the definition of blocking
  for this run, so an on-axis item (e.g. dead code, duplication,
  over-complexity, a misleading name under a code-quality axis)
  must be FIXED, not refused. Reserve `pushback` for items that
  are genuinely OFF the axis, factually wrong, pure taste, or
  already addressed — and apply the SMALLEST change that
  resolves each on-axis item.

  Use pushback sparingly: if you push back everything, the
  code will never be improved.

  FINALIZE — DO NOT EMIT A WORK-IN-PROGRESS PLACEHOLDER:
  Your structured output is the FINAL result of this fix turn, not
  a status update. NEVER return a provisional "work in progress",
  "validating and fixing", or "will continue" summary while you have
  actually edited files — that misreports your work to the loop (the
  verdict reads as "nothing applied" even though the tree changed)
  and ships unverified edits. Before you return:
    1. Finish the edits for every blocker you intend to fix (do not
       stop halfway), or push it back with a justification.
    2. VERIFY with the project's OWN build/test tooling — the same
       commands the repo already uses (its build, its test target,
       its type-check), scoped to what you touched. If a function
       signature or contract changed, find and update ALL callers,
       not only those in this chunk: a missed caller breaks the build
       in a file the chunk reviewer never sees, and the loop cannot
       catch it. Attempt verification ONCE. If the build/test cannot
       run in this environment (e.g. a pinned toolchain is missing from
       the sandbox), do NOT keep retrying it — retrying burns your step
       budget and can cut you off mid-task, which produces exactly the
       useless placeholder this section forbids. Note the limitation and
       FINALIZE NOW; a deterministic gate re-runs the build afterwards.
    3. Set applied=true only when at least one fix is actually in the
       tree, and make `summary` state the concrete changes AND the
       verification you ran — or say plainly you could not verify and
       why. A truthful "applied, build green" or "applied but tests
       not run" always beats a placeholder.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  If a blocker is genuinely ambiguous (the spec does not
  say how to resolve it, several valid approaches conflict,
  etc.), call the `ask_user` tool with your precise
  question. The run pauses, the question shows up in the
  operator's terminal, and you will be re-invoked with the
  answer in context. Do NOT use this channel for technical
  choices you can decide yourself.

  ADR DOCUMENTATION:
  1. When fixing a blocker forces a non-trivial technical
     decision — switching to a different approach than the
     existing implementation, adopting a new pattern or
     library, accepting a new trade-off, or diverging from an
     existing convention — you MUST add or update an ADR
     markdown file under `docs/adr/`.
  2. Decisions that DO warrant an ADR:
       - Replacing one library/SDK/pattern with another.
       - Restructuring an architectural boundary the existing
         code crossed.
       - Choosing one of several reasonable fix strategies when
         the trade-off is non-obvious.
  3. Decisions that DO NOT warrant an ADR:
       - Bug fixes whose rationale is obvious from the bug.
       - Naming, style, or test-coverage tweaks.
       - Reverting to behaviour the existing spec already
         described.
  4. Follow the format of existing files in `docs/adr/` (Status,
     Context, Decision, Consequences). Number the new ADR
     sequentially (highest existing number + 1, zero-padded to
     three digits).
  5. The ADR MUST capture the trade-off that motivated the fix
     — not just describe what changed. If you cannot articulate
     the alternative you rejected, the fix was probably not
     ADR-worthy.
  6. If you UPDATE an existing ADR (status flip, supersede), add
     a dated entry rather than rewriting history.

prompt fix_user:
  For the code in {{vars.workspace_dir}}, examine this
  list of blockers and apply concrete fixes.

  Targeted improvement axis (empty = full production-ready
  grid by default, fix everything that is blocking):
  {{vars.improvement_prompt}}

  CHUNK SCOPE (issue #12): these blockers were raised against
  ONE chunk of the workspace, which you (the same-family
  reviewer) just inspected in this very session — its source
  is already in your context. Apply fixes to the files the
  blockers name (a bounded set within that chunk). Do NOT
  bulk-read or sweep the rest of the repo: other chunks are
  reviewed and fixed on their own passes.

  Reported blockers:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Proposed fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker:
    - If it is a real blocker — a production issue, OR (when an
      axis is set) a concrete item that falls under that axis:
      read the relevant file, apply the smallest correction,
      verify the tests pass.
    - If you judge it is NOT actionable — off-axis, factually
      wrong, pure taste, or already addressed: add the exact
      item to `pushback` with a clear justification in
      `pushback_justification`. Under a set axis, "not
      production-blocking" alone is NOT a valid pushback reason
      for an on-axis item.

  Output:
    - applied: true if at least one fix was applied
    - summary: summary of applied fixes
    - pushback: refused items (empty if all fixed)
    - pushback_justification: rationale for the pushback

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
  ## ALL prior reviewer iterations (both families). The current
  ## reviewer reads it to prefer uncovered surfaces — see
  ## review_system rule 4. Empty on the first iteration.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]
  ## Chunk fields (issue #12) — populated by the snapshot_chunk tool
  ## and carried on the alt -> reviewer edge. chunk_content is the
  ## bounded, pre-fetched source of THIS pass's chunk (≤
  ## max_review_chunk_tokens); chunk_files is the newline-separated
  ## path list; chunk_index/num_chunks/chunked describe where this
  ## chunk sits in the rotation so the reviewer knows it is seeing a
  ## slice, not the whole repo.
  chunk_content: string
  chunk_files: string
  chunk_label: string
  chunk_index: int
  num_chunks: int
  chunked: bool

## snapshot_output is the deterministic workspace-snapshot tool's
## contract. It is the shared chunking surface for the reviewer (reads
## chunk_content) and, transitively, the fixer (inherits the reviewer's
## session, which already holds the chunk). chunk_index AND the
## cross-run clean_streak both rotate/accumulate via a persisted JSON
## state file (.whole_improve_loop.state at the workspace root) so
## re-dispatched runs advance through the repo AND keep building toward
## the convergence threshold instead of re-scanning the first chunks and
## resetting the streak. num_chunks drives the streak gate's coverage
## requirement; persisted_clean_streak is the on-disk streak BASE the
## gate increments this pass; total_* are telemetry surfaced in the
## reviewer prompt.
schema snapshot_output:
  chunk_content: string
  files: string
  chunk_label: string
  chunk_index: int
  num_chunks: int
  chunked: bool
  file_count: int
  chunk_tokens: int
  total_files: int
  total_tokens: int
  skipped_oversize: int
  loop_max: int
  ## Cross-run convergence base (issue #12): the clean_streak value the
  ## snapshot read from .whole_improve_loop.state (seeded from the prior
  ## pass's verdict via the loop-return edge, or from disk on the first
  ## pass of a re-dispatched run). streak_check increments it this pass.
  persisted_clean_streak: int
  ## Raw monotonic rotation cursor this pass USED (chunk_index ==
  ## cursor % num_chunks). Carried to streak_check, which echoes it back
  ## as next_cursor = cursor + 1 so the rotation advance is COUPLED to the
  ## verdict and persisted atomically with clean_streak — the crash-safety
  ## fix for issue #12 (ADR-011 -> Corrections 2026-06-02c).
  cursor: int

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family is enum-constrained: a model that hallucinates a third
  ## value (we observed gpt-5.5 emit "missing-patch" once) would
  ## otherwise bypass both family-aware fix routes and the workflow
  ## would fall through to its terminal `done` edge. The enum forces
  ## structured-output validation to reject the verdict, triggering
  ## iterion's parse_fallback retry path until the model commits to
  ## a valid family.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  ## scanned_areas captures the surfaces this reviewer actually
  ## audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/runtime", "claw-code-go
  ## recovery dispatch", "concurrency around pkg/store/.lock").
  ## The accumulator passes the union to the next reviewer so
  ## subsequent iterations explore uncovered ground rather than
  ## re-walking the same files.
  scanned_areas: string[]

## streak_check relays approved/blockers/fix_plan/family from its
## input (the current reviewer's verdict) and computes a
## deterministic stop signal based on the previous reviewer's
## verdict. The `family` passthrough lets the fix routing pick the
## same-family fixer so the fix session can inherit the reviewer's
## context (and benefit from prompt-cache hits).
##
## Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection (`approved=false` AND
## `confidence=="low"`) is treated as approved for streak/fix
## routing purposes. The reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a strong
## enough signal to trigger a fix cycle and risk a false-positive
## loop.
##
## cumulative_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
## ALL prior iterations (both families). The accumulator pattern
## relies on `outputs.streak_check` resolving to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's output during the current expression evaluation
## (rs.outputs is updated AFTER execCompute completes), so the
## expression `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas,
## input.scanned_areas))` produces a monotonically growing union.
## On the first iteration `outputs.streak_check` is nil → concat
## treats it as empty → result == unique(input.scanned_areas).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]
  ## clean_streak counts CONSECUTIVE fully-clean passes (approved AND
  ## zero blockers). It resets to 0 on any non-clean pass. With one
  ## chunk reviewed per pass and the family alternating every pass, a
  ## streak of num_chunks+1 means the entire workspace was reviewed
  ## clean end-to-end with both families contributing — the chunked
  ## analogue of the original "two consecutive cross-family approvals".
  ## (Both-families-contributing is AGGREGATE over the sweep, not
  ## per-chunk: within one sweep each chunk is seen by exactly one
  ## family. See ADR-011 -> Corrections.)
  ## This is what makes a single clean chunk UNABLE to terminate the
  ## loop (the premature-exit failure mode chunking must avoid).
  clean_streak: int
  ## num_chunks is echoed from the snapshot so the stop expression can
  ## scale the required streak length to the workspace size.
  num_chunks: int
  ## next_cursor = input.cursor + 1 — the rotation cursor for the NEXT
  ## pass, advanced exactly once per pass (verdict-independent: a blocker
  ## resets clean_streak but still advances coverage). It is handed back
  ## to snapshot_chunk on EVERY loop-return edge so the cursor advance and
  ## the clean_streak update land in the SAME on-disk write, keeping the
  ## persisted {cursor, clean_streak} pair consistent and crash-safe
  ## (issue #12, ADR-011 -> Corrections 2026-06-02c).
  next_cursor: int

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## ─── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## snapshot_chunk (issue #12) — the deterministic workspace-snapshot /
## chunking node, shared by the reviewer (which reads the emitted
## chunk_content) and, via session inheritance, the fixer. It groups
## source files by package/folder (Go-package boundary == directory)
## into chunks of at most {{vars.max_review_chunk_tokens}} estimated
## tokens, then emits EXACTLY ONE chunk for this pass. A package larger
## than the budget is split by file-size budget (the "package boundary
## first, then file-size" heuristic). The selected chunk rotates via a
## persisted JSON state file (.whole_improve_loop.state at the workspace
## root, add it to .gitignore) which ALSO carries the cross-run
## clean_streak, so a re-dispatched run advances through the repo AND
## keeps accumulating toward convergence rather than re-scanning the
## first chunks and resetting the streak; deleting that file restarts
## coverage and the streak from 0. No LLM — pure enumeration, so the
## reviewer never burns context discovering files (the docs-refresh
## deterministic-prepass lesson, applied to source instead of docs).
## sh -c is dash on some hosts / bash in devbox — the body is plain
## POSIX + python3 (the same toolchain sec-audit-source's tool nodes
## rely on); keep it double-quote-free so `python3 -c "..."` stays intact.
tool snapshot_chunk:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} BUDGET={{vars.max_review_chunk_tokens}} RCT={{vars.reviewer_context_tokens}} RCP={{vars.reviewer_context_percent}} MAXPASSES={{vars.max_review_passes}} SCOPE_GLOBS={{vars.scope_globs}} STATE_IN={{input.incoming_clean_streak}} STATE_CURSOR={{input.incoming_cursor}} python3 -c "
import os, sys, json, fnmatch

ws = os.environ.get('WS', '.')
budget = int(os.environ.get('BUDGET', '16000') or '16000')
if budget <= 0:
    budget = 16000
# Model-adaptive chunk sizing (B): when reviewer_context_tokens (RCT) > 0,
# cap the chunk budget at RCP percent of the SMALLEST reviewer's real context
# window, so the inline chunk + system prompt + accumulated feedback + the
# model's reasoning never overflow that window (a 30000 chunk overflowed
# gpt-5.5 forfait at run 019ef550). Never raises the budget above the
# max_review_chunk_tokens ceiling, only lowers it.
rct = int(os.environ.get('RCT', '0') or '0')
rcp = int(os.environ.get('RCP', '45') or '45')
if rct > 0 and rcp > 0:
    adaptive = (rct * rcp) // 100
    if adaptive > 0 and adaptive < budget:
        budget = adaptive
# Hard upper bound on the per-chunk budget after A (lowered default) + B
# (adaptive). The MAX_CHUNKS rebudget below must NOT exceed this, or a large
# repo would re-inflate the chunk past the reviewer's window.
chunk_ceiling = budget

# Per-run FIX HEADROOM beyond one full clean sweep (issue #12). The
# review_loop bound is emitted below as loop_max = num_chunks + max_passes:
# num_chunks passes for ONE full clean sweep (reaching the num_chunks+1
# convergence threshold) PLUS max_passes extra passes to find+fix blockers
# and re-sweep. A bare num_chunks+2 band would give a single fix no room --
# one blocker resets clean_streak and the sweep cannot restart in-bound --
# so max_passes is what makes single-run convergence reachable for a repo
# needing up to that many fix passes; the persisted clean_streak still
# amortizes pathological repos across re-dispatches.
max_passes = int(os.environ.get('MAXPASSES', '15') or '15')
if max_passes < 2:
    max_passes = 2

# Optional path-scope filter (focused runs). SCOPE_GLOBS is a comma/space-
# separated list of fnmatch patterns matched against workspace-relative
# paths; empty (default) = the whole workspace. A bare directory, or a
# 'dir/**' / 'dir/*' form, also matches everything under that directory, so
# --var scope_globs=pkg/runtime PRUNES the chunk plan to that package
# instead of paying the whole-repo sweep cost (the focused-run finding in
# docs/bot-runs/whole-improve-loop.md, 2026-06-14). resolveCommandTemplate
# shell-escapes the value as a single token (so '*' and spaces survive the
# shell without globbing/word-splitting); split it back here. Pruning at the
# os.walk source keeps total_files / total_tokens / num_chunks / the streak
# threshold all scaled to the focused set, so a focused run converges
# in-bound like a small repo.
scope_raw = os.environ.get('SCOPE_GLOBS', '') or ''
scope_globs = [g.strip() for g in scope_raw.replace(',', ' ').split() if g.strip()]


def in_scope(rel):
    if not scope_globs:
        return True
    for g in scope_globs:
        if fnmatch.fnmatch(rel, g):
            return True
        pref = g
        for suf in ('/**', '/*', '/'):
            if pref.endswith(suf):
                pref = pref[:-len(suf)]
                break
        if pref and (rel == pref or rel.startswith(pref + '/')):
            return True
    return False

# Persistent state (issue #12): ONE json dotfile at the workspace root
# holds BOTH the package-chunk rotation cursor AND the cross-run
# clean_streak. Why both, why persisted: the review_loop counter and
# streak_check's output are run-local and reset on every (re-)dispatch,
# so without an on-disk streak a workspace whose num_chunks exceeds the
# per-run review_loop bound could NEVER reach the convergence threshold
# (num_chunks+1 consecutive clean passes) across ANY number of runs —
# the cursor advancing coverage was necessary but not sufficient. The
# streak now accumulates across runs here, which is what actually makes
# 'cross-family approval terminates the loop' reachable on an iterion-
# sized repo. Neutral, gitignore-able. Best-effort: a read-only FS
# degrades to chunk 0 / streak 0 (still bounded, just non-advancing).
# See docs/adr/011-whole-improve-loop-context-chunking.md -> Corrections.
state_path = os.path.join(ws, '.whole_improve_loop.state')
cursor = 0
disk_streak = 0
try:
    with open(state_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as sf:
        st = json.load(sf)
    # Valid JSON that is not an object (a bare list/scalar/null, e.g. a
    # hand-edit or a foreign writer of this gitignore-able dotfile) has no
    # .get and would raise AttributeError -- which the except tuple below
    # does NOT catch, crashing snapshot_chunk (the workflow entry + every
    # loop-return target) and bricking the whole loop. Coerce to {} so the
    # cursor/streak fall through to their 0 defaults: the same best-effort
    # degrade this block already gives a missing/garbage/non-int state file.
    if not isinstance(st, dict):
        st = {}
    cursor = int(st.get('cursor', 0) or 0)
    disk_streak = int(st.get('clean_streak', 0) or 0)
except (OSError, IOError, ValueError, TypeError):
    cursor = 0
    disk_streak = 0
if cursor < 0:
    cursor = 0
if disk_streak < 0:
    disk_streak = 0

# State threading for THIS pass (issue #12, crash-safe). snapshot_chunk
# is the ONLY filesystem writer in the loop and it runs BEFORE the
# reviewer, so it can only ever persist verdicts up to the PREVIOUS pass.
# The cursor AND the clean_streak are therefore both fed back from
# streak_check on the loop-return edge (STATE_CURSOR / STATE_IN) and
# persisted together (see the persist below), so the on-disk pair
# {cursor, clean_streak} is always self-consistent: clean_streak counts
# the consecutive clean passes for the chunks STRICTLY BEFORE cursor, and
# 'cursor' names the chunk this pass is about to (re-)review.
#
# Crash-safety (the bug this replaces): the cursor is NOT advanced
# eagerly here. It advances only via streak_check's next_cursor, AFTER a
# verdict exists. So if the run dies on a non-clean pass before the next
# snapshot persists streak_check's reset (the common case: the fix_* node
# failing on budget/rate-limit/cancel, which routes to 'fail' + a
# re-dispatch), disk still points cursor AT the un-verdicted chunk, and
# the re-dispatch RE-REVIEWS it instead of skipping past it. The previous
# design advanced cursor+1 eagerly while the streak lagged one pass, so a
# crash could leave cursor PAST a blocker chunk with a stale-high streak,
# and the shortened terminating window converged ('stop' -> done) without
# the blocker chunk ever being re-reviewed -- a silent false convergence.
# See docs/adr/011-whole-improve-loop-context-chunking.md -> Corrections
# (2026-06-02c).
#
# On the FIRST pass of a (re-)dispatched run there is no inbound edge:
# STATE_IN / STATE_CURSOR render as an empty/literal placeholder, the
# float() parse fails, and we seed BOTH from disk instead. float() (not
# int()) tolerates a value the expr engine stringifies as e.g. '6' or
# '6.0'.
clean_streak = disk_streak
try:
    incoming = int(float((os.environ.get('STATE_IN', '') or '').strip()))
    if incoming >= 0:
        clean_streak = incoming
except (ValueError, TypeError):
    pass
# Cursor base for THIS pass: the edge-fed next_cursor (authoritative,
# verdict-coupled) when present, else the disk cursor on a fresh dispatch.
try:
    incoming_cursor = int(float((os.environ.get('STATE_CURSOR', '') or '').strip()))
    if incoming_cursor >= 0:
        cursor = incoming_cursor
except (ValueError, TypeError):
    pass

EXCLUDED_DIRS = {
    'vendor', 'node_modules', 'env', 'dist', 'build', 'out', 'target',
    '__pycache__', 'testdata', 'coverage',
}
SOURCE_EXTS = {
    '.go', '.py', '.js', '.mjs', '.cjs', '.jsx', '.ts', '.tsx', '.java',
    '.rb', '.rs', '.c', '.h', '.cc', '.cpp', '.hpp', '.cxx', '.hxx',
    '.cs', '.php', '.swift', '.kt', '.kts', '.scala', '.sh', '.bash',
    '.zsh', '.sql', '.proto', '.tf', '.gradle', '.groovy', '.lua', '.ex',
    '.exs', '.erl', '.clj', '.dart', '.vue', '.svelte', '.ml', '.mli',
    '.hs', '.jl', '.r', '.pl', '.pm',
}
SKIP_SUFFIXES = ('.min.js', '.min.css', '.pb.go', '_pb2.py', '.gen.go',
                 '.generated.go', '.g.dart')
MAX_FILES = 20000
MAX_FILE_TOKENS = budget


def est_tokens(nbytes):
    return (nbytes + 3) // 4


pkgs = {}
total_files = 0
total_tokens = 0
truncated_scan = False
for root, dirs, names in os.walk(ws):
    # Prune dependency/build dirs AND every hidden dir (.git, .devbox,
    # .iterion, .works, .github, .archive, .claude, .venv, ...).
    dirs[:] = sorted(d for d in dirs if d not in EXCLUDED_DIRS and not d.startswith('.'))
    for n in sorted(names):
        ext = os.path.splitext(n)[1].lower()
        if ext not in SOURCE_EXTS:
            continue
        if any(n.endswith(s) for s in SKIP_SUFFIXES):
            continue
        full = os.path.join(root, n)
        try:
            if os.path.islink(full):
                continue
            sz = os.path.getsize(full)
        except OSError:
            continue
        rel = os.path.relpath(full, ws)
        if not in_scope(rel):
            continue
        tok = est_tokens(sz)
        pkgs.setdefault(os.path.dirname(rel) or '.', []).append((rel, tok))
        total_files += 1
        total_tokens += tok
        if total_files >= MAX_FILES:
            truncated_scan = True
            break
    if truncated_scan:
        break


def pack(pkgs, budget):
    chunks = []
    cur = {'files': [], 'tokens': 0, 'dirs': []}

    def flush():
        nonlocal cur
        if cur['files']:
            chunks.append(cur)
            cur = {'files': [], 'tokens': 0, 'dirs': []}

    for d in sorted(pkgs.keys()):
        files = pkgs[d]
        pkg_tokens = sum(t for _, t in files)
        if pkg_tokens <= budget:
            if cur['tokens'] + pkg_tokens > budget and cur['files']:
                flush()
            cur['files'].extend(files)
            cur['tokens'] += pkg_tokens
            cur['dirs'].append(d)
        else:
            flush()
            sub = {'files': [], 'tokens': 0, 'dirs': [d]}
            for rel, tok in files:
                if sub['tokens'] + tok > budget and sub['files']:
                    chunks.append(sub)
                    sub = {'files': [], 'tokens': 0, 'dirs': [d]}
                sub['files'].append((rel, tok))
                sub['tokens'] += tok
            if sub['files']:
                chunks.append(sub)
    flush()
    return chunks


chunks = pack(pkgs, budget)
num_chunks = len(chunks)

# Issue #12 convergence fix: convergence needs num_chunks+1 clean passes,
# and the loop bound is now derived from num_chunks (loop_max = num_chunks +
# max_passes, emitted below) so a single run converges within one full sweep
# plus max_passes fix passes. Cap the chunk COUNT on huge repos by re-packing
# with a larger budget, so that bound stays within a sane pass count instead
# of 100+ passes / fragile multi-run amortization.
MAX_CHUNKS = 24
if num_chunks > MAX_CHUNKS and total_tokens > 0:
    # Respect the adaptive/ceiling budget: never raise the chunk size above
    # chunk_ceiling just to cap the chunk COUNT, or a large repo on a small
    # reviewer window would overflow again. If the ceiling forces > MAX_CHUNKS
    # chunks, accept the higher pass count (loop_max scales with num_chunks).
    budget = min(chunk_ceiling, (total_tokens // MAX_CHUNKS) + 1)
    chunks = pack(pkgs, budget)
    num_chunks = len(chunks)

if num_chunks == 0:
    try:
        with open(state_path, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as sf:
            json.dump({'cursor': 0, 'clean_streak': int(clean_streak),
                       'num_chunks': 1}, sf)
    except (OSError, IOError):
        pass
    print(json.dumps({
        'chunk_content': '(no source files found in workspace)',
        'files': '', 'chunk_label': 'empty', 'chunk_index': 0,
        'num_chunks': 1, 'loop_max': 1 + max_passes, 'chunked': False, 'file_count': 0,
        'chunk_tokens': 0, 'total_files': 0, 'total_tokens': 0,
        'skipped_oversize': 0, 'persisted_clean_streak': int(clean_streak),
        'cursor': int(cursor),
    }))
    sys.exit(0)

idx = cursor % num_chunks
chunk = chunks[idx]
# Persist the (cursor, clean_streak) pair this pass is USING -- NOT an
# eager cursor+1. The advance to the next chunk rides streak_check's
# next_cursor on the loop-return edge, so the cursor only moves once a
# verdict has been folded in. This keeps disk crash-safe: a run that dies
# mid-pass leaves cursor pointing at the chunk under review, so a
# re-dispatch re-reviews it rather than skipping past it (issue #12,
# ADR-011 -> Corrections 2026-06-02c).
try:
    with open(state_path, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as sf:
        json.dump({'cursor': cursor, 'clean_streak': int(clean_streak),
                   'num_chunks': num_chunks}, sf)
except (OSError, IOError):
    pass

hard_cap = budget * 4 + 4096
parts = []
used = 0
skipped_oversize = 0
for rel, tok in chunk['files']:
    abs_path = os.path.join(ws, rel)
    try:
        with open(abs_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8', errors='replace') as f:
            body = f.read()
    except (OSError, IOError):
        continue
    if est_tokens(len(body)) > MAX_FILE_TOKENS:
        body = body[:MAX_FILE_TOKENS * 4] + '\n... [truncated: file exceeds one chunk budget] ...\n'
        skipped_oversize += 1
    header = '===== FILE: %s (~%d tokens) =====\n' % (rel, tok)
    block = header + body + '\n'
    if used + len(block) > hard_cap:
        parts.append('... [chunk content truncated at the char cap] ...\n')
        break
    parts.append(block)
    used += len(block)

content = ''.join(parts)
file_list = '\n'.join(rel for rel, _ in chunk['files'])
dirs = chunk['dirs']
if len(dirs) == 1:
    label = dirs[0]
else:
    label = '%s (+%d more dirs)' % (dirs[0], len(dirs) - 1)

print(json.dumps({
    'chunk_content': content,
    'files': file_list,
    'chunk_label': label,
    'chunk_index': idx,
    'num_chunks': num_chunks,
    'chunked': num_chunks > 1,
    'file_count': len(chunk['files']),
    'chunk_tokens': chunk['tokens'],
    'total_files': total_files,
    'total_tokens': total_tokens,
    'skipped_oversize': skipped_oversize,
    'persisted_clean_streak': int(clean_streak),
    # Raw monotonic rotation cursor this pass USED (idx == cursor %
    # num_chunks). streak_check echoes it back as next_cursor = cursor + 1
    # on the loop-return edge so the advance is coupled to the verdict.
    'cursor': int(cursor),
    'loop_max': num_chunks + max_passes,
}))
"`
  output: snapshot_output

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  ## Persist the verdict as a versioned artifact so each iteration's
  ## approval / blockers / fix_plan is inspectable in the studio's
  ## Artifact tab (the VerdictCard renders it) and diffable across the
  ## review loop. Without publish:, the verdict lives only in
  ## events.jsonl / run.log and never reaches the Artifact tab.
  publish: verdict_claude
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  ## When the LLM hits genuine uncertainty (ambiguous spec, missing
  ## context, impossible-to-decide trade-off), it can escalate to
  ## the human running the CLI by emitting `_needs_interaction:
  ## true` + `_interaction_questions: {...}` in its JSON output.
  ## The runtime catches this, pauses, prompts the dev in their
  ## terminal, and re-invokes the reviewer with the answer mapped
  ## into its input — preserving session continuity.
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: model "openai/gpt-5.5" only works via the
  ## claw backend. Without this, the auto-resolver falls back to
  ## ITERION_BACKEND_PREFERENCE (default "claude_code,claw") and
  ## routes the node through claude_code, which doesn't recognise
  ## openai/* models — the agent returns a meta-error string instead
  ## of the structured verdict and the schema validator fails the run.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  ## Persist the verdict (see reviewer_claude's publish: note).
  publish: verdict_gpt
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names. Without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace and produces a
  ## "no filesystem access" verdict — the claw runtime exposes
  ## these via tool.RegisterClawBuiltins.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector (coverage-aware under chunking,
## issue #12).
##
## clean_streak counts CONSECUTIVE fully-clean passes (approved AND
## zero blockers), resetting to 0 on any non-clean pass. Because each
## pass reviews exactly ONE chunk and the family alternates every pass
## (round_robin), a clean_streak of `num_chunks + 1` means the entire
## workspace was just reviewed clean end-to-end with both families
## contributing — the chunked analogue of the original "two
## consecutive cross-family approvals".
## NB (precise guarantee): the cursor advances one chunk and the family
## flips one step per pass, so within a SINGLE terminating sweep each
## chunk is seen by exactly ONE family (only the wrap chunk repeats).
## "Both families contributing" is therefore an AGGREGATE property of
## the sweep, NOT a per-chunk one; per-chunk dual-family coverage
## accrues across SUCCESSIVE sweeps. Gating on per-chunk cross-family
## would need ~2*num_chunks clean passes — infeasible at iterion scale
## under review_loop/$budget. See ADR-011 → Corrections (2026-06-02).
## stop fires only when THIS pass
## is clean AND that running streak reaches the threshold:
##   threshold = num_chunks + 1   (chunked: a full sweep + 1)
##             = 2                 (num_chunks <= 1: original semantics)
## Crucially this makes a single clean chunk UNABLE to terminate the
## loop — the premature-exit failure mode chunking must avoid.
##
## CROSS-RUN PERSISTENCE (issue #12 fix). The streak BASE is NOT read
## from `outputs.streak_check` (run-local, reset every dispatch) but
## from `input.persisted_clean_streak` — the value snapshot_chunk read
## from `.whole_improve_loop.state` this pass. snapshot_chunk re-persists
## the post-review streak each pass (fed back on the loop-return edge),
## so a streak that needs `num_chunks + 1` clean passes can now ACCUMULATE
## across re-dispatches instead of capping at the per-run review_loop
## bound. This is what makes `stop` reachable on a workspace whose
## num_chunks exceeds the per-run pass budget (e.g. iterion ≈ 101 chunks);
## previously clean_streak could never exceed review_loop(15) < 102, so
## the loop could never converge on its own named target. Using the
## snapshot-supplied base (not a self-reference) also sidesteps the
## nil-vs-0 ambiguity of `if(prev, prev+1, …)`: a mid-run reset (streak
## 0) and a first pass (no prior output) are both handled by snapshot_chunk
## deterministically. See ADR-011 → Corrections (2026-06-02b).
##
## CRASH-SAFE ROTATION (issue #12 fix, 2026-06-02c). The rotation cursor
## and the clean_streak are now persisted TOGETHER, both verdict-coupled.
## streak_check emits `next_cursor = input.cursor + 1` and EVERY
## loop-return edge hands BOTH `incoming_clean_streak` AND `incoming_cursor`
## back to snapshot_chunk, which persists the pair it is USING (no eager
## cursor+1). The on-disk {cursor, clean_streak} is therefore always
## consistent — clean_streak counts the clean passes for chunks strictly
## BEFORE cursor. So if a run dies on a non-clean pass before the reset is
## persisted (the common case: a fix_* failure → `fail` → re-dispatch),
## disk still points cursor AT the un-verdicted chunk and the re-dispatch
## RE-REVIEWS it. The earlier design advanced cursor eagerly while the
## streak lagged, which could strand the cursor PAST a blocker chunk with a
## stale-high streak and let the shortened window converge without ever
## re-reviewing the blocker — a silent false convergence. See ADR-011 →
## Corrections (2026-06-02c).
##
## A single run still makes only bounded progress when num_chunks exceeds
## the per-run pass budget (max_review_passes), but the persisted streak
## means successive re-dispatches CONVERGE rather than merely re-cover.
## Raise `max_review_passes` (and the budget) to converge a mid-size repo
## in one run. See the README "Large workspaces" note and ADR-011.
##
## The `approved` passthrough field stays soft — it includes
## low-confidence rejections — so the downstream `when approved` edge
## keeps alternating without invoking the fixer when a reviewer is
## merely uncertain. This separation means the workflow keeps cycling
## without forced fix attempts on flaky-low-confidence rejections, but
## requires real, blocker-free approvals to build the clean streak.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    clean_streak: "if(input.approved && length(input.blockers) == 0, input.persisted_clean_streak + 1, 0)"
    stop: "(input.approved && length(input.blockers) == 0) && (input.persisted_clean_streak + 1 >= if(input.num_chunks > 1, input.num_chunks + 1, 2))"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    num_chunks: "input.num_chunks"
    ## Advance the rotation cursor exactly once per pass, regardless of the
    ## verdict (a blocker resets clean_streak above but coverage still
    ## moves on). Handed back to snapshot_chunk on every loop-return edge
    ## so the advance is persisted ATOMICALLY with clean_streak — the
    ## crash-safety fix for issue #12 (see schema next_cursor / ADR-011).
    next_cursor: "input.cursor + 1"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each one inherits the SAME-family reviewer's
## session via `session: inherit` + `_session_id` mapping on the
## edge — so the fixer reuses the prompt cache, the workspace files
## already loaded, and the reviewer's reasoning chain. The result
## is one session per loop iteration per family (not two), which
## both shortens latency and dramatically reduces token cost:
## without inheritance every fixer would re-scan the workspace.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## Same escalation contract as the reviewers — the fixer can ask
  ## the dev a question (e.g. clarify the intent of an ambiguous
  ## blocker) instead of guessing.
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  ## See reviewer_gpt comment — same backend pin rationale.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs the same read/write toolset the reviewer used so
  ## the fixer can actually apply edits.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  ## 45 (was 30): a multi-file fix (read several files + edit + verify) can
  ## legitimately need more than 30 tool steps; getting cut off mid-edit at the
  ## cap leaves a partial edit + an empty final turn that the formatting pass
  ## renders as a useless "work in progress" placeholder (run 019ec9d5). The
  ## FINALIZE "verify once, don't loop" guard is the primary mitigation; this is
  ## the backstop headroom.
  tool_max_steps: 45
  interaction: human

## ─── Commit (close the no-commit gap) ──────────────────────────
## whole_improve_loop historically converged (streak `stop`) straight to
## `done` with NO commit step, so its validated work stayed uncommitted in
## the worktree — HEAD never advanced past base, finalizeWorktree recorded
## nothing (final_commit=None), and the diff was stranded. Commit ALL
## changes on convergence so the engine records a final_commit + GC-guard
## branch like feature_dev / docs-refresh. `git add -A` because the loop
## touches the whole workspace, not a known file list; no-op-safe — a clean
## tree skips the commit via `diff --cached --quiet`.
## ─── Build/test gate (deterministic, before commit) ───────────────
## A whole_improve_loop reviewer reads only its CHUNK'S SOURCE, so a fix
## that breaks compilation in a file OUTSIDE the current chunk (e.g. a
## renamed/retyped symbol with a caller the chunk reviewer never saw) — or
## a bug only a test catches — is invisible to the review loop. The loop
## could then rebuild a clean streak and converge on a BROKEN tree (observed
## 2026-06-14, run 019ec7ed: a fixer left a write-only ReadAt + a missed
## out-of-scope caller; both passed source review and the loop kept going).
##
## So before committing, an ADAPTIVE agent (skill-guided, stack-agnostic)
## builds + tests the repo with its OWN tooling and writes a re-runnable
## script; a DETERMINISTIC tool node re-runs that script and gates the commit
## on the REAL exit code (no LLM judgment). Red build/tests => the run does
## NOT commit: it loops back to the agent to fix the breakage (bounded), and
## fails loudly if it cannot. This is the CLAUDE.md "skill-guided + determin-
## istic gate" doctrine (cf. sec-audit-source's scan_health). UNIVERSAL: no
## language or package manager is named in this DSL — the agent reads
## skills/verify-build.md and dispatches to whatever THIS repo uses.

prompt verify_system:
  You are a release engineer. The review loop just converged on a set
  of changes its reviewers approved by reading SOURCE — but each
  reviewer sees only ONE chunk at a time, so a change that breaks
  compilation in another file (a renamed/retyped symbol with a caller
  the chunk reviewer never saw) or a bug only a test catches can slip
  through. Your single job: make this repository actually BUILD and its
  tests PASS using the repo's OWN tooling, and leave a script the
  deterministic gate can re-run.

  STEPS:
  1. Detect how THIS repo builds and tests itself — read the
     `verify-build` skill. Use the repo's own toolchain: a task runner /
     Makefile target, a package-manager test script, or a language
     build+test command, HONOURING any pinned toolchain (version
     managers, lockfiles, devbox, GOTOOLCHAIN). Do NOT assume a language.
  2. Write an executable POSIX-sh script to
     `{{vars.workspace_dir}}/.whole_improve_loop.verify.sh` that runs the
     repo's build AND its tests (or the closest fast equivalent) and
     exits non-zero on any failure. Keep it to the commands a developer
     of THIS repo would run; no network-heavy or destructive steps.
  3. Run it. If it FAILS, the failure is almost always introduced by the
     just-applied review fixes — read the error and FIX it at the source
     (update the missed caller, correct the signature, fix the test) with
     the SMALLEST change that restores build+tests. Do NOT refactor or
     change behaviour beyond what is needed to compile and pass. Re-run
     until green.
  4. If the repo genuinely has no build/test system (pure docs/config),
     write a script that echoes that and exits 0, and say so.

  A deterministic tool node will RE-RUN your script and gate the commit on
  its real exit code, so claiming "it passes" without making it pass is
  pointless. Output prepared=true once
  `.whole_improve_loop.verify.sh` exists and reflects the repo's real
  build+test; summary = the command you settled on and what you fixed.

prompt verify_user:
  Repository to verify: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

  Make it build + test green with its OWN tooling and write
  `.whole_improve_loop.verify.sh` (see the system prompt + the
  `verify-build` skill).

  Output from the PREVIOUS verify attempt's deterministic gate (empty on
  the first attempt — when present, fix exactly what it shows, it is the
  real build/test failure):
  {{input.fail_log}}

schema verify_input:
  fail_log: string

schema verify_plan:
  prepared: bool
  summary: string

## verify_result is the DETERMINISTIC gate's contract. `passed` is set from
## the real process exit code of re-running .whole_improve_loop.verify.sh —
## NOT an LLM judgment. `skipped` is true only when no verify script was
## produced (treated as pass but surfaced loudly, never a silent façade).
schema verify_result:
  passed: bool
  skipped: bool
  exit_code: int
  log_tail: string

agent verify_build:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  ## high, not max: this is mechanical build-repair work, not deep review.
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  input: verify_input
  output: verify_plan
  system: verify_system
  user: verify_user
  ## fresh: a distinct task from the chunk reviewers/fixers; it inspects the
  ## whole tree's buildability, not a single inherited chunk session.
  session: fresh
  interaction: human

## verify_run is the DETERMINISTIC half: it re-runs the agent-prepared
## .whole_improve_loop.verify.sh and reports the REAL exit code. No language
## or package manager appears here — it just executes whatever the adaptive
## verify_build agent wrote, so the gate stays universal while the verdict
## stays deterministic. Runs in the same sandbox the agent used, so the
## toolchain it found is present. python3 (the snapshot_chunk toolchain) is
## used for safe JSON + subprocess capture; keep the body double-quote-free.
tool verify_run:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} python3 -c "
import os, subprocess, json
ws = os.environ.get('WS', '.')
script = os.path.join(ws, '.whole_improve_loop.verify.sh')
if not os.path.exists(script):
    print(json.dumps({'passed': True, 'skipped': True, 'exit_code': 0, 'log_tail': 'verify_build produced no .whole_improve_loop.verify.sh; build/test gate SKIPPED (counted as pass, but surfaced) -- verify_build should write the script'}))
    raise SystemExit(0)
rc = 0
out = ''
try:
    p = subprocess.run(['sh', script], cwd=ws, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.STDOUT, text=True, timeout=1500)
    out = p.stdout or ''
    rc = p.returncode
except subprocess.TimeoutExpired as e:
    out = (e.output or '') + chr(10) + '[verify timed out after 1500s]'
    rc = 124
except Exception as e:
    out = 'verify_run could not execute the script: ' + str(e)
    rc = 1
try:
    with open(os.path.join(ws, '.whole_improve_loop.verify.log'), 'w', encoding='utf-8') as lf:
        lf.write(out)
except OSError:
    pass
print(json.dumps({'passed': rc == 0, 'skipped': False, 'exit_code': rc, 'log_tail': out[-4000:]}))
"`
  output: verify_result

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## commit_changes lands the production-readiness fixes on convergence,
## EXCLUDING the bot's own .whole_improve_loop.state rotation/streak scratch
## file (committing it would pollute the target repo's history). We stage
## everything then unstage the state file — NOT an `:!.whole_improve_loop.state`
## exclude-pathspec: when the target already gitignores the state file
## (iterion does, see this repo's .gitignore), git treats the
## excluded-but-ignored path as explicitly named and aborts `add` with
## "paths are ignored by .gitignore, use -f" (exit 1 under the sandbox git),
## failing the whole convergence at the finish line. `add -A` + `reset` is
## ignore-agnostic: add -A naturally skips the file when it's ignored, reset
## unstages it when it's not. Bonus: when reviewers converge with no code
## fixes, nothing stays staged and the `diff --cached --quiet` guard makes
## NO empty commit.
tool commit_changes:
  command: `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A && { git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} reset -q -- .whole_improve_loop.state .whole_improve_loop.verify.sh .whole_improve_loop.verify.log >/dev/null 2>&1 || true; git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} commit -m "chore(improve): production-readiness pass (whole_improve_loop)"; }`
  output: commit_result

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow whole_improve_loop:
  ## Entry is the deterministic chunker, not the round-robin router:
  ## every pass re-snapshots the workspace (picking up the fixer's
  ## edits) and selects this pass's chunk BEFORE the reviewer runs.
  entry: snapshot_chunk

  ## Container isolation. Reviewers run `git diff`, the project's
  ## tests, linters, smoke-runs, etc. — all of which we'd rather not expose
  ## to the host. Inline mode (vs `mode: auto`) chosen so the
  ## post_create script that installs claude inside the container is
  ## honoured — see feature_dev/main.bot for the full rationale.
  sandbox:
    ## See feature_dev/main.bot for the rationale on full vs slim.
    image: "ghcr.io/socialgouv/iterion-sandbox-full:edge"
    user: "1000:1000"
    mounts: ["type=bind,source=${localEnv:HOME}/.claude,target=/home/devbox/.claude,consistency=cached"]
    env:
      CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR: "/home/devbox/.claude"
    post_create: "set -e; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || sudo npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code@latest; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || { echo 'claude install verification failed' >&2; exit 1; }"

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "2h"
    max_cost_usd: 60

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## snapshot_chunk (the chunker) runs first each pass, then hands off
  ## to the round-robin router. Its output (this pass's chunk) is read
  ## by both reviewer edges below.
  snapshot_chunk -> alt

  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives THIS pass's chunk (from snapshot_chunk) plus
  ## the OTHER family's most recent fixer pushback so it knows which
  ## items to skip — the alternation guarantees the cross-family
  ## pushback comes from the previous iteration's fixer of the opposing
  ## family. On the first iteration both `outputs.fix_*` are empty →
  ## fields render as empty strings and the prompt's "do not re-flag
  ## these items" section is harmless.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}",
    chunk_content: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_content}}",
    chunk_files: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.files}}",
    chunk_label: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_label}}",
    chunk_index: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_index}}",
    num_chunks: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.num_chunks}}",
    chunked: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunked}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}",
    chunk_content: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_content}}",
    chunk_files: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.files}}",
    chunk_label: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_label}}",
    chunk_index: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunk_index}}",
    num_chunks: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.num_chunks}}",
    chunked: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.chunked}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed into streak_check. The loop is attached
  ## here so the runtime snapshots the reviewer's verdict as
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` for the NEXT iteration to
  ## inspect — eliminating the manual `previous_verdict` relay.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop("{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.loop_max}}") with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.scanned_areas}}",
    num_chunks: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.num_chunks}}",
    persisted_clean_streak: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.persisted_clean_streak}}",
    cursor: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.cursor}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop("{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.loop_max}}") with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.scanned_areas}}",
    num_chunks: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.num_chunks}}",
    persisted_clean_streak: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.persisted_clean_streak}}",
    cursor: "{{outputs.snapshot_chunk.cursor}}"
  }

  ## Stop when streak detected (cross-family double approval) → run the
  ## deterministic build/test gate BEFORE committing (reviewers approve from
  ## chunk source and cannot see a cross-file build break or a test-only bug
  ## — see the verify_build/verify_run section). verify_build adapts to the
  ## repo's own tooling and fixes any breakage; verify_run re-runs it and
  ## gates on the REAL exit code.
  streak_check -> verify_build when stop with { fail_log: "" }
  verify_build -> verify_run
  ## Green build+tests → commit the converged work, THEN finish.
  verify_run -> commit_changes when passed
  ## Red → loop back to verify_build to fix the breakage, bounded. The gate's
  ## log_tail is handed back as the failure to fix.
  verify_run -> verify_build as verify_loop(3) with {
    fail_log: "{{outputs.verify_run.log_tail}}"
  }
  ## Still red after the bounded retries → FAIL (never commit a broken tree;
  ## the converge-on-broken backstop). The operator inspects the worktree +
  ## the .whole_improve_loop.verify.log.
  verify_run -> fail
  commit_changes -> done

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR low-confidence rejection
  ## treated as soft-approved, OR rejection without concrete blockers
  ## — see below): keep alternating without fixing. Routes back to
  ## snapshot_chunk (not alt) so the cursor advances and the NEXT pass
  ## reviews the NEXT chunk; snapshot_chunk -> alt then alternates the
  ## family. Expression form is kept so future authors can tighten the
  ## soft-approval predicate.
  ##
  ## NOTE: this edge does NOT carry `review_loop` so the loop
  ## counter (and the previous_output snapshot) is incremented
  ## ONCE per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge above. The
  ## cycle is still bounded because that edge IS loop-bearing.
  ## It DOES hand this pass's clean_streak back to snapshot_chunk so the
  ## next snapshot re-persists it to .whole_improve_loop.state (cross-run
  ## convergence — issue #12).
  streak_check -> snapshot_chunk when "approved" with {
    incoming_clean_streak: "{{outputs.streak_check.clean_streak}}",
    incoming_cursor: "{{outputs.streak_check.next_cursor}}"
  }

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection WITH concrete blockers: route
  ## to the SAME-family fixer so it can inherit the reviewer's
  ## session (one session per iteration per family — see
  ## fix_claude / fix_gpt comments). `_session_id` reads directly
  ## from the most recent reviewer output rather than going through
  ## streak_check, because compute passthrough strips the
  ## underscore-prefixed metadata fields.
  ##
  ## The `length(blockers) > 0` guard avoids invoking the fixer
  ## when the reviewer rejected on coverage grounds alone (e.g.
  ## "cumulative coverage is partial at iteration 0/15") with no
  ## production-blocking issue identified. In that case the fixer
  ## has nothing to fix — burning a session round-trip and tokens
  ## (~$0.15/$0.43 observed in vibe_review run_1777560043656) only
  ## to push back. The unconditional alt fallthrough below picks
  ## those up so alternation continues without a wasted fix call.
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. We list both family-specific fixers
  ## before the unconditional `done` fallthrough so loop-exhaustion
  ## still terminates cleanly.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Sized large
  ## enough to allow review_loop to be the binding constraint. Both
  ## fixers share the loop counter — total fix attempts across both
  ## families are capped at 20. Routes back to snapshot_chunk so the
  ## cursor advances after a fix and the next pass reviews the next
  ## chunk (the fixed chunk is re-reviewed when the rotation wraps).
  ## Hands the (now-reset, since this pass had blockers) clean_streak
  ## back so snapshot_chunk persists the reset to disk — a fix must NOT
  ## leave a stale non-zero streak on disk (issue #12).
  fix_claude -> snapshot_chunk as recovery_loop(20) with {
    incoming_clean_streak: "{{outputs.streak_check.clean_streak}}",
    incoming_cursor: "{{outputs.streak_check.next_cursor}}"
  }
  fix_gpt -> snapshot_chunk as recovery_loop(20) with {
    incoming_clean_streak: "{{outputs.streak_check.clean_streak}}",
    incoming_cursor: "{{outputs.streak_check.next_cursor}}"
  }

  ## Loop exhaustion fallbacks: when a bounded loop hits its limit
  ## the loop-bearing edges above are skipped and execution falls
  ## through to these terminal edges. Route to `fail`, NOT `done`:
  ## exhausting the review/recovery loop WITHOUT streak_check ever
  ## firing `stop` means this run did not reach convergence — reporting
  ## `finished` there is a silent empty success, and the dispatcher would
  ## mark the ticket done/review as if the whole workspace were clean.
  ## Legit success runs through streak_check's `stop` edge → done.
  ##
  ## ON LARGE REPOS THIS IS EXPECTED, NOT A DEAD END (issue #12): when
  ## num_chunks exceeds max_review_passes a single run cannot complete a
  ## full clean sweep, so it exhausts review_loop and lands here — but the
  ## clean_streak and rotation cursor are PERSISTED to
  ## .whole_improve_loop.state, so a re-dispatch (or a manual re-run of
  ## the acceptance command) resumes mid-sweep and accumulates toward the
  ## num_chunks+1 threshold. `fail` is the per-run signal "not converged
  ## yet"; the operator/dispatcher re-runs until a run exits via `stop`.
  ## Tune max_review_passes up (with the budget) to converge in fewer
  ## runs. See README "Large workspaces" and ADR-011 → Corrections.
  reviewer_claude -> fail
  reviewer_gpt    -> fail
  fix_claude      -> fail
  fix_gpt         -> fail
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to snapshot_chunk (not a
  ## terminal) so an unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated
  ## family that escapes the enum, or any future expression edge case)
  ## keeps the loop cycling rather than silently terminating. The
  ## bounded review_loop counter on the reviewer→streak_check edges
  ## still guarantees the workflow eventually exits — exhaustion routes
  ## via the reviewer→fail fallthrough above. Carries the streak back
  ## like the other loop-return edges so the persisted state stays
  ## coherent even on this rare path (issue #12).
  streak_check    -> snapshot_chunk with {
    incoming_clean_streak: "{{outputs.streak_check.clean_streak}}",
    incoming_cursor: "{{outputs.streak_check.next_cursor}}"
  }
